# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lysine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lysine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The stereoisomer (*S*)-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (also referred to as L-P5C) is an intermediate metabolite in the biosynthesis and degradation of proline and arginine.
[src:lysine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In prokaryotic proline biosynthesis, GSA is synthesized from γ-glutamyl phosphate by the enzyme γ-glutamyl phosphate reductase.
[src:lysine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In most eukaryotes, GSA is synthesised from the amino acid glutamate by the bifunctional enzyme 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthase (P5CS).
[src:lysine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The human P5CS is encoded by the *ALDH18A1* gene.
[src:lysine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The enzyme pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase converts L-P5C into proline.
[src:lysine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In proline degradation, the enzyme proline dehydrogenase produces P5C from proline, and the enzyme 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate dehydrogenase converts GSA to glutamate.
[src:lysine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In many prokaryotes, proline dehydrogenase and P5C dehydrogenase form a bifunctional enzyme that prevents the release of P5C during proline degradation.
[src:lysine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] A reciprocal regulation of delta 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthetase (P5CS) and proline dehydrogenase genes controls proline levels during and after osmotic stress in plants proportional to the level of proline.
[src:lysine/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] This allows an optimum level of proline to be produced from reduced nitrogen to control osmotic stress.
[src:lysine/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] The enzyme 3-hydroxyanthranilate 3,4-dioxygenase uses oxygen to cleave the aromatic ring of 3-hydroxyanthranilic acid, giving 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde.
[src:lysine/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] The kynurenine pathway of tryptophan catabolism leads to nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide and supplies the nicotinic acid component of that cofactor.
[src:lysine/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] Alternatively, 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde can be acted on by the enzyme aminocarboxymuconate-semialdehyde decarboxylase to give 2-aminomuconic semialdehyde, an unstable open-chain precursor of picolinic acid.
[src:lysine/2-aminoadipate-transaminase] The two substrates of this enzyme are L-2-aminoadipic acid and α-Ketoglutaric acid.
[src:lysine/2-aminoadipate-transaminase] Its products are 2-oxoadipic acid and L-glutamic acid.
[src:lysine/2-aminoadipate-transaminase] This enzyme belongs to the family of transferases, specifically the transaminases, which transfer nitrogenous groups.
[src:lysine/2-aminoadipate-transaminase] The systematic name of this enzyme class is **L-2-aminoadipate:2-oxoglutarate aminotransferase**.
[src:lysine/2-aminoadipate-transaminase] Other names in common use include **alpha-aminoadipate aminotransferase**, **2-aminoadipate aminotransferase**, **2-aminoadipic aminotransferase**, **glutamic-ketoadipic transaminase**, and **glutamate-alpha-ketoadipate transaminase**.
[src:lysine/2-aminoadipate-transaminase] This enzyme participates in lysine biosynthesis and lysine degradation.
[src:lysine/2-aminoadipate-transaminase] It employs one cofactor, pyridoxal phosphate.
[src:lysine/2-aminoadipate-transaminase] As of late 2007, only one structure has been solved for this class of enzymes, with the PDB accession code PDB: 2DTV.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-acid] 2-Aminomuconic acid is a six-carbon molecule bearing two carboxyl groups, two conjugated double bonds, and a primary amino substituent at carbon 2.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-acid] The molecule is commonly encountered in its ionized form, 2-aminomuconate, under physiological and environmental aqueous conditions.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Specific physical constants such as pKa values, solubility, and spectroscopic data are not comprehensively tabulated in the primary literature and should be added only with a verified source.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-acid] In microbial biodegradation of aromatic xenobiotics, for example certain nitroaromatic compounds, where ring-cleavage pathways produce aminomuconic intermediates prior to further downstream processing.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-acid] The compound appears as a catabolic intermediate in several bacterial strains studied under laboratory conditions.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-acid] In the oxidative degradation of tryptophan via the kynurenine pathway, intermediates with structural relation to aminomuconate are formed during enzymatic ring opening and aldehyde oxidation steps.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Wherever it appears, the ionized form 2-aminomuconate is typically the biologically relevant species.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Details such as kinetic constants, mechanism and gene names vary by organism and strain and should be cited from the primary enzymology literature for each specific claim.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-acid] In environmental microbiology, pathways involving 2-aminomuconate are part of bacterial systems that allow mineralization of aromatic pollutants, converting recalcitrant compounds into metabolites that join central carbon metabolism.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-acid] Such pathways are of interest for biodegradation and bioremediation research.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-semialdehyde] 2-Aminomuconic semialdehyde is an intermediate in the kynurenine pathway of tryptophan metabolism, which leads to picolinic acid or quinolinic acid.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-semialdehyde] The enzyme aminocarboxymuconate-semialdehyde decarboxylase produces it from 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde, a compound which would form quinolinic acid in the absence of that enzyme.
[src:lysine/2-aminomuconic-semialdehyde] 2-Aminomuconic semialdehyde itself is chemically unstable and spontaneously ring-closes to picolinic acid, with loss of water.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] The **2-oxoadipate dehydrogenase complex** (**OADHC**, **OADHc**) or **α-ketoadipate dehydrogenase complex** is a mitochondrial, multienzyme complex, most commonly known for its role in the degradation of lysine, tryptophan and hydroxylysine.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] It belongs to the 2-oxoacid dehydrogenase complex family.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] The OADHC can also process 2-oxopimelate, a non-native substrate, but does so over 100 times less efficiently than its natural substrate, 2-oxoadipate.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] OADHC catalyzes the oxidative decarboxylation of 2-oxoadipate to glutaryl-CoA in the lysine and tryptophan degradation pathway.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] Glutaryl-CoA can act as an acyl group donor for lysine glutarylation, a non-enzymatic post-translational modification.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] OADHC itself has been shown to undergo autoglutarylation, which may inhibit its activity and create a feedback regulatory loop.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] The mitochondrial sirtuin SIRT5 can remove glutaryl groups in a NAD+-dependent manner.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] The OADHC produces superoxide and hydrogen peroxide at levels comparable to the flavin site of Complex I, a known source of mitochondrial reactive oxygen species (ROS).
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] However, its activity is much lower than that of other related enzymes—approximately sevenfold lower than the 2-oxoglutarate dehydrogenase complex (OGDC), fourfold lower than the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDC), and about half that of the branched-chain α-ketoacid dehydrogenase complex (BCKDC).
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] ROS production increases when the NAD(P)H to NAD(P)+ ratio is high, but only during the forward reaction where 2-oxoadipate is converted into glutaryl-CoA.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] In contrast, reverse electron flow through isolated E3 with NADH does not generate ROS, indicating that full substrate turnover by the intact complex is required.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] The ROS-producing site within OADHC appears to be a flavin-containing region distinct from that in OGDC.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] OADHC thus represents a mitochondrial ROS source and is part of the NADH isopotential pool—a group of enzymes with similar redox characteristics that generate ROS under highly reduced conditions.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] The 2-oxoadipate dehydrogenase complex (OADHC) is one of four mitochondrial 2-oxoacid dehydrogenase complexes, alongside the 2-oxoglutarate dehydrogenase complex (OGDC), the branched-chain α-ketoacid dehydrogenase complex (BCKDC), and pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDC).
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] Notably, OADHC and OGDC share the same E2 component (DLST), while PDC and BCKDC utilize distinct E2 components.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] All four complexes, however, share the same E3 component and depend on the same essential cofactors: thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP), lipoic acid, FAD, NAD+, and CoA.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] Beyond its similarities with other members of the 2-oxoacid dehydrogenase complex family, OADHC also shares key features with the glycine cleavage system (GCS).
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] Instead of being a three-component multienzyme complex, the GCS consists of four distinct proteins (P, H, T, and L), with the L-protein being identical to the E3 component (DLD) found in 2-oxoacid dehydrogenase complexes.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] Like the latter, the GCS depends on common cofactors such as lipoic acid, FAD, and NAD+.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] Unlike the 2-oxoacid dehydrogenase complexes, the GCS uniquely requires tetrahydrofolate (THF).
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] This shared use of the E3/DLD component highlights a core biochemical link between the 2-oxoacid dehydrogenase complexes and the GCS, despite their distinct substrates, cofactor dependencies, and roles in ROS production and metabolic regulation.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] Biallelic mutations in the *DHTKD1* gene, which encodes the E1a component of the OADHC, cause a rare autosomal recessive disorder known as alpha-aminoadipic and alpha-oxoadipic aciduria (AMOXAD).
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] This condition leads to accumulation of 2-oxoadipate and 2-aminoadipate in plasma and urine due to impaired degradation of lysine, hydroxylysine, and tryptophan.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] Clinical symptoms vary widely, ranging from asymptomatic biochemical abnormalities to developmental delay, epilepsy, or hypotonia.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] The precise clinical significance of these metabolite accumulations remains unclear.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] Defects in mitochondrial lipoylation pathways can impair multiple 2-oxoacid dehydrogenase complexes, including the OADHC.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] In fibroblasts from individuals with LIPT1 deficiency, reduced OADHC-dependent metabolic flux has been observed.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] While the effects on OADHC are less thoroughly characterized than for PDHC or OGDHC, the findings indicate that OADHC activity is also sensitive to impaired lipoylation.
[src:lysine/2-oxoadipate-dehydrogenase-complex] Unlike 2-oxoglutarate dehydrogenase complex, the "2-" in 2-oxoadipate dehydrogenase complex should not be omitted, as "oxoadipate" alone could refer to other isomers such as 3-oxoadipate.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:lysine/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:lysine/lysine] The human body cannot synthesize lysine.
[src:lysine/lysine] It is essential in humans and must therefore be obtained from the diet.
[src:lysine/lysine] In organisms that synthesize lysine, two main biosynthetic pathways exist, the diaminopimelate and α-aminoadipate pathways, which employ distinct enzymes and substrates and are found in diverse organisms.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine catabolism occurs through one of several pathways, the most common of which is the saccharopine pathway.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine plays several roles in humans, most importantly proteinogenesis, but also in the crosslinking of collagen polypeptides, uptake of essential mineral nutrients, and in the production of carnitine, which is key in fatty acid metabolism.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine is also often involved in histone modifications, and thus, impacts the epigenome.
[src:lysine/lysine] The ε-amino group often participates in hydrogen bonding and as a general base in catalysis.
[src:lysine/lysine] The ε-ammonium group (−NH+3) is attached to the fourth carbon from the α-carbon, which is attached to the carboxyl (−COOH) group.
[src:lysine/lysine] Due to its importance in several biological processes, a lack of lysine can lead to several disease states including defective connective tissues, impaired fatty acid metabolism, anaemia, and systemic protein-energy deficiency.
[src:lysine/lysine] In contrast, an overabundance of lysine, caused by ineffective catabolism, can cause severe neurological disorders.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine was first isolated by the German biological chemist Ferdinand Heinrich Edmund Drechsel in 1889 from hydrolysis of the protein casein, and thus named it Lysin, from Greek λύσις*(lysis)* 'loosening'.
[src:lysine/lysine] In 1902, the German chemists Emil Fischer and Fritz Weigert determined lysine's chemical structure by synthesizing it.
[src:lysine/lysine] The one-letter symbol K was assigned to lysine for being alphabetically nearest, with L being assigned to the structurally simpler leucine, and M to methionine.
[src:lysine/lysine] Two pathways have been identified in nature for the synthesis of lysine.
[src:lysine/lysine] The diaminopimelate (DAP) pathway belongs to the aspartate derived biosynthetic family, which is also involved in the synthesis of threonine, methionine and isoleucine, whereas the α-aminoadipate (AAA) pathway is part of the glutamate biosynthetic family.
[src:lysine/lysine] The product is then reduced by dihydrodipicolinate reductase (DHDPR) (E.C 1.3.1.26), with NAD(P)H as a proton donor, to yield 2,3,4,5-tetrahydrodipicolinate (THDP).
[src:lysine/lysine] From this point on, four pathway variations have been found, namely the acetylase, aminotransferase, dehydrogenase, and succinylase pathways.
[src:lysine/lysine] Both the acetylase and succinylase variant pathways use four enzyme catalysed steps, the aminotransferase pathway uses two enzymes, and the dehydrogenase pathway uses a single enzyme.
[src:lysine/lysine] These four variant pathways converge at the formation of the penultimate product, *meso*‑diaminopimelate, which is subsequently enzymatically decarboxylated in an irreversible reaction catalysed by diaminopimelate decarboxylase (DAPDC) (E.C 4.1.1.20) to produce L-lysine.
[src:lysine/lysine] The DAP pathway is regulated at multiple levels, including upstream at the enzymes involved in aspartate processing as well as at the initial DHDPS catalysed condensation step.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine imparts a strong negative feedback loop on these enzymes and, subsequently, regulates the entire pathway.
[src:lysine/lysine] The AAA pathway involves the condensation of α-ketoglutarate and acetyl-CoA via the intermediate AAA for the synthesis of L-lysine.
[src:lysine/lysine] This pathway has been shown to be present in several yeast species, as well as protists and higher fungi.
[src:lysine/lysine] It has also been reported that an alternative variant of the AAA route has been found in *Thermus thermophilus* and *Pyrococcus horikoshii*, which could indicate that this pathway is more widely spread in prokaryotes than originally proposed.
[src:lysine/lysine] The first and rate-limiting step in the AAA pathway is the condensation reaction between acetyl-CoA and α‑ketoglutarate catalysed by homocitrate-synthase (HCS) (E.C 2.3.3.14) to give the intermediate homocitryl‑CoA, which is hydrolysed by the same enzyme to produce homocitrate.
[src:lysine/lysine] Homocitrate is enzymatically dehydrated by homoaconitase (HAc) (E.C 4.2.1.36) to yield *cis*-homoaconitate.
[src:lysine/lysine] HAc then catalyses a second reaction in which *cis*-homoaconitate undergoes rehydration to produce homoisocitrate.
[src:lysine/lysine] The resulting product undergoes an oxidative decarboxylation by homoisocitrate dehydrogenase (HIDH) (E.C 1.1.1.87) to yield α‑ketoadipate.
[src:lysine/lysine] AAA is then formed via a pyridoxal 5′-phosphate (PLP)-dependent aminotransferase (PLP-AT) (E.C 2.6.1.39), using glutamate as the amino donor.
[src:lysine/lysine] From this point on, the AAA pathway varies with [something is missing here ? -> at the very least, section header! ] on the kingdom.
[src:lysine/lysine] In fungi, AAA is reduced to α‑aminoadipate-semialdehyde via AAA reductase (E.C 1.2.1.95) in a unique process involving both adenylation and reduction that is activated by a phosphopantetheinyl transferase (E.C 2.7.8.7).
[src:lysine/lysine] Once the semialdehyde is formed, saccharopine reductase (E.C 1.5.1.10) catalyses a condensation reaction with glutamate and NAD(P)H, as a proton donor, and the imine is reduced to produce the penultimate product, saccharopine.
[src:lysine/lysine] The final step of the pathway in fungi involves the saccharopine dehydrogenase (SDH) (E.C 1.5.1.8) catalysed oxidative deamination of saccharopine, resulting in L-lysine.
[src:lysine/lysine] In a variant AAA pathway found in some prokaryotes, AAA is first converted to *N*‑acetyl-α-aminoadipate, which is phosphorylated and then reductively dephosphorylated to the ε-aldehyde.
[src:lysine/lysine] The aldehyde is then transaminated to *N*‑acetyllysine, which is deacetylated to give L-lysine.
[src:lysine/lysine] However, the enzymes involved in this variant pathway need further validation.
[src:lysine/lysine] As with all amino acids, catabolism of lysine is initiated from the uptake of dietary lysine or from the breakdown of intracellular protein.
[src:lysine/lysine] Catabolism is also used as a means to control the intracellular concentration of free lysine and maintain a steady-state to prevent the toxic effects of excessive free lysine.
[src:lysine/lysine] There are several pathways involved in lysine catabolism but the most commonly used is the saccharopine pathway, which primarily takes place in the liver (and equivalent organs) in animals, specifically within the mitochondria.
[src:lysine/lysine] This is the reverse of the previously described AAA pathway.
[src:lysine/lysine] The first step involves the LKR catalysed reduction of L-lysine in the presence of α-ketoglutarate to produce saccharopine, with NAD(P)H acting as a proton donor.
[src:lysine/lysine] Saccharopine then undergoes a dehydration reaction, catalysed by SDH in the presence of NAD+, to produce AAS and glutamate.
[src:lysine/lysine] AAS dehydrogenase (AASD) (E.C 1.2.1.31) then further dehydrates the molecule into AAA.
[src:lysine/lysine] Subsequently, PLP-AT catalyses the reverse reaction to that of the AAA biosynthesis pathway, resulting in AAA being converted to α-ketoadipate.
[src:lysine/lysine] The product, α‑ketoadipate, is decarboxylated in the presence of NAD+ and coenzyme A to yield glutaryl-CoA, however the enzyme involved in this is yet to be fully elucidated.
[src:lysine/lysine] Some evidence suggests that the 2-oxoadipate dehydrogenase complex (OADHc), which is structurally homologous to the E1 subunit of the oxoglutarate dehydrogenase complex (OGDHc) (E.C 1.2.4.2), is responsible for the decarboxylation reaction.
[src:lysine/lysine] Finally, glutaryl-CoA is oxidatively decarboxylated to crotonyl-CoA by glutaryl-CoA dehydrogenase (E.C 1.3.8.6), which goes on to be further processed through multiple enzymatic steps to yield acetyl-CoA; an essential carbon metabolite involved in the tricarboxylic acid cycle (TCA).
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine is an essential amino acid in humans.
[src:lysine/lysine] The human daily nutritional requirement varies from ~60 mg/kg in infancy to ~30 mg/kg in adults.
[src:lysine/lysine] This requirement is commonly met in a western society with the intake of lysine from meat and vegetable sources well in excess of the recommended requirement.
[src:lysine/lysine] In vegetarian diets, the intake of lysine is less due to the limited quantity of lysine in cereal crops compared to meat sources.
[src:lysine/lysine] Given the limiting concentration of lysine in cereal crops, it has long been speculated that the content of lysine can be increased through genetic modification practices.
[src:lysine/lysine] Often these practices have involved the intentional dysregulation of the DAP pathway by means of introducing lysine feedback-insensitive orthologues of the DHDPS enzyme.
[src:lysine/lysine] These methods have met limited success likely due to the toxic side effects of increased free lysine and indirect effects on the TCA cycle.
[src:lysine/lysine] Plants accumulate lysine and other amino acids in the form of seed storage proteins, found within the seeds of the plant, and this represents the edible component of cereal crops.
[src:lysine/lysine] This highlights the need to not only increase free lysine, but also direct lysine towards the synthesis of stable seed storage proteins, and subsequently, increase the nutritional value of the consumable component of crops.
[src:lysine/lysine] While genetic modification practices have met limited success, more traditional selective breeding techniques have allowed for the isolation of "Quality Protein Maize", which has significantly increased levels of lysine and tryptophan, also an essential amino acid.
[src:lysine/lysine] This increase in lysine content is attributed to an *opaque-2* mutation that reduced the transcription of lysine-lacking zein-related seed storage proteins and, as a result, increased the abundance of other proteins that are rich in lysine.
[src:lysine/lysine] Commonly, to overcome the limiting abundance of lysine in livestock feed, industrially produced lysine is added.
[src:lysine/lysine] The industrial process includes the fermentative culturing of *Corynebacterium glutamicum* and the subsequent purification of lysine.
[src:lysine/lysine] Good sources of lysine are high-protein foods such as eggs, meat (specifically red meat, lamb, pork, and poultry), soy, beans and peas, cheese (particularly Parmesan), and certain fish (such as cod and sardines).
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine is the limiting amino acid (the essential amino acid found in the smallest quantity in the particular foodstuff) in most cereal grains, but is plentiful in most pulses (legumes).
[src:lysine/lysine] Beans contain the lysine that maize lacks, and in the human archeological record beans and maize often appear together, as in the Three Sisters: beans, maize, and squash.
[src:lysine/lysine] A food is considered to have sufficient lysine if it has at least 51 mg of lysine per gram of protein (so that the protein is 5.1% lysine).
[src:lysine/lysine] L-lysine HCl is used as a dietary supplement, providing 80.03% L-lysine.
[src:lysine/lysine] As such, 1 g of L-lysine is contained in 1.25 g of L-lysine HCl.
[src:lysine/lysine] The most common role for lysine is proteinogenesis.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine frequently plays an important role in protein structure.
[src:lysine/lysine] Since its side chain contains a positively charged group on one end and a long hydrophobic carbon tail close to the backbone, lysine is considered somewhat amphipathic.
[src:lysine/lysine] For this reason, lysine can be found buried as well as more commonly in solvent channels and on the exterior of proteins, where it can interact with the aqueous environment.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine can also contribute to protein stability as its ε-amino group often participates in hydrogen bonding, salt bridges and covalent interactions to form a Schiff base.
[src:lysine/lysine] A second major role of lysine is in epigenetic regulation by means of histone modification.
[src:lysine/lysine] There are several types of covalent histone modifications, which commonly involve lysine residues found in the protruding tail of histones.
[src:lysine/lysine] Modifications often include the addition or removal of an acetyl (−CH3CO) forming acetyllysine or reverting to lysine, up to three methyl (−CH3), ubiquitin or a sumo protein group.
[src:lysine/lysine] The various modifications have downstream effects on gene regulation, in which genes can be activated or repressed.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine has also been implicated to play a key role in other biological processes including; structural proteins of connective tissues, calcium homeostasis, and fatty acid metabolism.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine has been shown to be involved in the crosslinking between the three helical polypeptides in collagen, resulting in its stability and tensile strength.
[src:lysine/lysine] This mechanism is akin to the role of lysine in bacterial cell walls, in which lysine (and *meso*-diaminopimelate) are critical to the formation of crosslinks, and therefore, stability of the cell wall.
[src:lysine/lysine] This concept has previously been explored as a means to circumvent the unwanted release of potentially pathogenic genetically modified bacteria.
[src:lysine/lysine] It was proposed that an auxotrophic strain of *Escherichia coli* (X1776) could be used for all genetic modification practices, as the strain is unable to survive without the supplementation of DAP, and thus, cannot live outside of a laboratory environment.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine has also been proposed to be involved in calcium intestinal absorption and renal retention, and thus, may play a role in calcium homeostasis.
[src:lysine/lysine] Finally, lysine has been shown to be a precursor for carnitine, which transports fatty acids to the mitochondria, where they can be oxidised for the release of energy.
[src:lysine/lysine] Carnitine is synthesised from trimethyllysine, which is a product of the degradation of certain proteins, as such lysine must first be incorporated into proteins and be methylated prior to being converted to carnitine.
[src:lysine/lysine] However, in mammals the primary source of carnitine is through dietary sources, rather than through lysine conversion.
[src:lysine/lysine] In opsins like rhodopsin and the visual opsins (encoded by the genes OPN1SW, OPN1MW, and OPN1LW), retinaldehyde forms a Schiff base with a conserved lysine residue, and interaction of light with the retinylidene group causes signal transduction in color vision (See visual cycle for details).
[src:lysine/lysine] There has been a long discussion that lysine, when administered intravenously or orally, can significantly increase the release of growth hormones.
[src:lysine/lysine] This has led to athletes using lysine as a means of promoting muscle growth while training, however, no significant evidence to support this application of lysine has been found to date.
[src:lysine/lysine] Because herpes simplex virus (HSV) proteins are richer in arginine and poorer in lysine than the cells they infect, lysine supplements have been tried as a treatment.
[src:lysine/lysine] Since the two amino acids are taken up in the intestine, reclaimed in the kidney, and moved into cells by the same amino acid transporters, an abundance of lysine would, in theory, limit the amount of arginine available for viral replication.
[src:lysine/lysine] Clinical studies do not provide good evidence for effectiveness as a prophylactic or in the treatment for HSV outbreaks.
[src:lysine/lysine] In response to product claims that lysine could improve immune responses to HSV, a review by the European Food Safety Authority found no evidence of a cause–effect relationship.
[src:lysine/lysine] The same review, published in 2011, found no evidence to support claims that lysine could lower cholesterol, increase appetite, contribute to protein synthesis in any role other than as an ordinary nutrient, or increase calcium absorption or retention.
[src:lysine/lysine] Diseases related to lysine are a result of the downstream processing of lysine, i.e., the incorporation into proteins or modification into alternative biomolecules.
[src:lysine/lysine] The role of lysine in collagen has been outlined above, however, a lack of lysine and hydroxylysine involved in the crosslinking of collagen peptides has been linked to a disease state of the connective tissue.
[src:lysine/lysine] As carnitine is a key lysine-derived metabolite involved in fatty acid metabolism, a substandard diet lacking sufficient carnitine and lysine can lead to decreased carnitine levels, which can have significant cascading effects on an individual's health.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine has also been shown to play a role in anaemia, as lysine is suspected to have an effect on the uptake of iron and, subsequently, the concentration of ferritin in blood plasma.
[src:lysine/lysine] However, the exact mechanism of action is yet to be elucidated.
[src:lysine/lysine] Most commonly, lysine deficiency is seen in non-western societies and manifests as protein-energy malnutrition, which has profound and systemic effects on the health of the individual.
[src:lysine/lysine] There is also a hereditary genetic disease that involves mutations in the enzymes responsible for lysine catabolism, namely the bifunctional AASS enzyme of the saccharopine pathway.
[src:lysine/lysine] Due to a lack of lysine catabolism, the amino acid accumulates in plasma and patients develop hyperlysinaemia, which can present as asymptomatic to severe neurological disabilities, including epilepsy, ataxia, spasticity, and psychomotor impairment.
[src:lysine/lysine] The clinical significance of hyperlysinemia is the subject of debate in the field with some studies finding no correlation between physical or mental disabilities and hyperlysinemia.
[src:lysine/lysine] In addition to this, mutations in genes related to lysine metabolism have been implicated in several disease states, including pyridoxine-dependent epilepsia (ALDH7A1 gene), α-ketoadipic and α-aminoadipic aciduria (DHTKD1 gene), and glutaric aciduria type 1 (GCDH gene).
[src:lysine/lysine] Hyperlysinuria is marked by high amounts of lysine in the urine.
[src:lysine/lysine] It is often due to a metabolic disease in which a protein involved in the breakdown of lysine is non functional due to a genetic mutation.
[src:lysine/lysine] It may also occur due to a failure of renal tubular transport.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine production for animal feed is a major global industry, reaching in 2009 almost 700,000 tons for a market value of over €1.22 billion.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine is an important additive to animal feed because it is a limiting amino acid when optimizing the growth of certain animals such as pigs and chickens for the production of meat.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine supplementation allows for the use of lower-cost plant protein (maize, for instance, rather than soy) while maintaining high growth rates, and limiting the pollution from nitrogen excretion.
[src:lysine/lysine] In turn, however, phosphate pollution is a major environmental cost when corn is used as feed for poultry and swine.
[src:lysine/lysine] Lysine is industrially produced by microbial fermentation, from a base mainly of sugar.
[src:lysine/lysine] Genetic engineering research is actively pursuing bacterial strains to improve the efficiency of production and allow lysine to be made from other substrates.
[src:lysine/lysine] The most common bacteria used is Corynebacterium glutamicum specially mutagenized or gene-engineered to produce lysine, but analogous strains of Escherichia coli are also employed.
[src:lysine/lysine] The 1993 film *Jurassic Park*, which is based on the 1990 novel *Jurassic Park* by Michael Crichton, features dinosaurs that were genetically altered so that they could not produce lysine, an example of engineered auxotrophy.
[src:lysine/lysine] This was known as the "lysine contingency" and was supposed to prevent the cloned dinosaurs from surviving outside the park, forcing them to depend on lysine supplements provided by the park's veterinary staff.
[src:lysine/lysine] In reality, no animal can produce lysine; it is an essential amino acid.
[src:lysine/lysine] In 1996, lysine became the focus of a price-fixing case, the largest in United States history.
[src:lysine/lysine] The Archer Daniels Midland Company paid a fine of US$100 million, and three of its executives were convicted and served prison time.
[src:lysine/lysine] Also found guilty in the price-fixing case were two Japanese firms (Ajinomoto, Kyowa Hakko) and a South Korean firm (Sewon).
[src:lysine/lysine] Secret video recordings of the conspirators fixing lysine's price can be found online or by requesting the video from the U.S.
[src:lysine/lysine] Department of Justice, Antitrust Division.
[src:lysine/lysine] This case gave the basis for the book *The Informant: A True Story*, and the movie *The Informant!*.
